04776nam a22008295i 9789814695077DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20152015si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898146950777 a10.1355/97898146950772doi  a(DE-B1597)522064  a(OCoLC)1102800608  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 4aDS526.7b.T74 no. 10 7aPOL0110002bisacsh04a338.4336309512231 aTang, Siew Mun, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Politics of the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB) /cSiew Mun Tang. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (25 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tThe Politics of the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB). EXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tThe Politics of the Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB). INTRODUCTION -- tASIA’S THIRST FOR INFRASTRUCTURE FUNDING -- tMEMBERSHIP: WHO’S IN, WHO’S OUT? -- tIMPLICATIONS OF THE AIIB’S EXPANDING MEMBERSHIP -- tEUROPE’S PARTICIPATION AS A GAME CHANGER -- tTHE STRATEGIC IMPACT OF THE AIIB -- tTHE DYNAMICS OF INSTITUTIONAL DESIGN -- tIMPLICATIONS AND LESSONS FOR SOUTHEAST ASIA -- tCONCLUSION0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAsia needs US$8.22 trillion to fund its infrastructure investment from 2010 to 2020, and existing lending institutions such as the ADB are unable to meet these requirements. The Asian Infrastructure Investment Bank (AIIB) can potentially provide up to US$30 billion of funding a year. Every geographical region, except North and Central America, is represented in the AIIB. The United States and Japan are the only East Asia Summit members not in the AIIB. The participation of European countries transforms the AIIB from a regional institution with a singular power base (China) to an entity that is broad-based and inclusive. Washington's response to the AIIB initiative has been a strategic misreading that failed to anticipate its allies reactions in warming up to and eventually supporting the proposal. East Asian countries will now be watching what effect the Chinese initiative and American non-participation will have on the U.S. rebalance to Asia.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aAsian Infrastructure Investment Bank. 0aAsia—Foreign economic relations—China. 0aBanking. 0aChina—Foreign economic relations—Asia. 0aInfrastructure (Economics)zAsiaxFinance. 0aInfrastructure (Economics)—Asia—Finance. 4aBanks & Banking. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aMun, Tang Siew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2015 Part 2z978311076664608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2015z978311070098508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066300608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017z978311060667640uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981469507740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814695077423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789814695077/original  a978-3-11-060667-6  ISEAS eBook Package 2015-2017c2015d2017  a978-3-11-066300-6  ISEAS Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-070098-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2015b2015  a978-3-11-076664-6  DG Plus PP Package 2015 Part 2b2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK